            <ul>
              <li>InMail credits for cold outreach</li>
              <li>Who viewed your profile (full list)</li>
              <li>LinkedIn Learning access</li>
              <li>Applicant insights for job seekers</li>
              <li>Best for: active job seekers and recruiters</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for LinkedIn Creator Mode</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Choose topic hashtags strategically.</strong> Pick 5 hashtags where your ideal audience already gathers. Don't choose the most popular ones — choose the most specific ones where your content will stand out. #ContentMarketing (5M+ followers) is harder to penetrate than #B2BContentMarketing (50K followers).</li>
          <li><strong>Publish before you enable.</strong> Have at least 10 posts published before turning Creator Mode on. New visitors who arrive at your profile after the algorithm surfaces your content need to see a content library, not an empty featured section.</li>
          <li><strong>Launch a newsletter on day one.</strong> Creator Mode's newsletter auto-invite feature sends invitations to all your existing connections. You only get this batch invite once — use it on launch, not 6 months later after connections have grown cold.</li>
          <li><strong>Maintain posting consistency, not frequency.</strong> The LinkedIn algorithm rewards consistency over volume. 3 posts per week every week outperforms 10 posts one week and 0 the next.</li>
          <li><strong>Use LinkedIn Live for time-sensitive events.</strong> LinkedIn Live notifications go to followers directly. Use it for product launches, AMAs, and industry events — not evergreen content that performs fine as a recorded video.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit your hashtag choices quarterly.</strong> Topic hashtags aren't permanent. Review them every 3 months to confirm they still reflect your content focus and attract the right audience segments.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — enabling Creator Mode without a publishing plan</div>
          <p>Creator Mode amplifies your existing content activity. If you toggle it on and then post once a month, the only thing it changes is that visitors see an empty Featured section. The algorithm boost only materializes when you give it content to distribute. Set a realistic publishing cadence — even 2 posts per week — before enabling.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common LinkedIn Creator Mode mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Using generic hashtags</strong> — #Marketing and #Business have millions of followers but your posts get buried. Go specific.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring the newsletter launch window</strong> — LinkedIn's auto-invite to connections only fires once at newsletter creation. Timing it well matters.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating Creator Mode as a passive setting</strong> — The mode is a tool. The results come from your publishing. Enabling it without a content calendar changes nothing.</li>
          <li><strong>Disconnecting from connection requests</strong> — Some creators set their profile to Follow-only and miss genuine business connections. Keep connections open; just let Follow be the default.</li>
          <li><strong>Posting without a consistent voice</strong> — Creator Mode surfaces your content to new audiences. If your posts lack a consistent perspective or topic focus, new followers won't stick.</li>
        </ul>

